{"id":"patt-sol/9801003","submitter":"Thierry Gallay","authors":"Thierry Gallay (Paris XI) and Alexander Mielke (Hannover)","title":"Diffusive Mixing of Stable States in the Ginzburg-Landau Equation","comments":"28 pages, LaTeX","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1007/s002200050495","report-no":"98-06 (Math. preprint, University of Paris XI)","categories":"patt-sol nlin.PS","license":null,"abstract":"  For the time-dependent Ginzburg-Landau equation on the real line, we\nconstruct solutions which converge, as $x \\to \\pm\\infty$, to periodic\nstationary states with different wave-numbers $\\eta_\\pm$. These solutions are\nstable with respect to small perturbations, and approach as $t \\to +\\infty$ a\nuniversal diffusive profile depending only on the values of $\\eta_\\pm$. This\nextends a previous result of Bricmont and Kupiainen by removing the assumption\nthat $\\eta_\\pm$ should be close to zero. The existence of the diffusive profile\nis obtained as an application of the theory of monotone operators, and the\nlong-time behavior of our solutions is controlled by rewriting the system in\nscaling variables and using energy estimates involving an exponentially growing\ndamping term.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 27 Jan 1998 08:33:11 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
{"id":"quant-ph/9801061","submitter":"Antoine Suarez","authors":"Antoine Suarez (Center for Quantum Philosophy, Zurich)","title":"Does Quantum Mechanics imply influences acting backward in time in\n  impact series experiments?","comments":"9 pages Latex, 1 eps figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  A real two-particle experiment is proposed in which one of the particles\nundergoes two successive impacts on beam-splitters. It is shown that the\nstandard quantum mechanical superposition principle implies the possibility of\ninfluences acting backward in time (\"retrocausation\"), in striking contrast\nwith the principle of causality. It is argued that nonlocality and\nretrocausation are not necessarily entangled.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 26 Jan 1998 17:13:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
